{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"654c8c4c-6b59-4896-a1bb-9b852f672196","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is an application-level runtime bug, not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs from mscoree.dll) only cover **runtime selection and loading** — things like:\n\n- Which CLR version the shim picks\n- Whether the runtime loads at all\n- .NET 3.5 Feature-on-Demand dialogs\n\nThey won't contain information about NullReferenceExceptions.\n\n**To diagnose your NullReferenceException, you'd want to look at:**\n1. The **exception stack trace** (from app logs, Event Viewer, or debugger)\n2. A **crash dump** collected via `dotnet-dump` or Windows Error Reporting\n3. **Application-level logs**\n\nDo you have any of those artifacts? Or if you do suspect a CLR activation problem (e.g., wrong runtime loading, app failing to start), I can invoke the CLR activation debugging skill to help with that instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"48c94532-44b5-473a-98da-454263fcf957","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, a NullReferenceException after startup is not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs are about the process of loading and selecting the correct CLR version — things like shim behavior, runtime version selection, and .NET 3.5 Feature-on-Demand dialogs. A NullReferenceException is an application-level bug, not an activation problem.\n\n\nI need to clarify this mismatch with the user. Even though they explicitly asked to analyze CLR activation logs, those logs won't help diagnose a NullReferenceException — they show how the runtime was loaded, not why the application code is throwing exceptions at runtime. The skill isn't the right tool for this particular problem.","outputTokens":577,"requestId":"A0C2:2B902C:BD3856:EB9BCA:6A013206"},"id":"6ff83d2f-68a6-44e9-9bcd-16cb9f358fda","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:34:13.078Z","parentId":"b89be398-fafe-4427-9f4f-2fe52b1e4a91"}
